  "text": "In this second test I compared the return rates of adult and subadult females for difficult-toacquire fruits. Subadult females (ages 5-7 years) have completed most of their growth [CITATION_1] and are therefore likely to be nearly as strong as adult females, but do not begin to reproduce until age 7 on average [CITATION_2] . Male capuchins, on the other hand, do not attain full body size until well after the subadult period and thus are less useful for trying to disentangle the roles of skill versus strength in determining return rates. If adult females have higher return rates for difficult-to-acquire fruits than do subadult females, it is likely that these differences stem largely from differences in skill rather than from differences in strength.",
